  - name: employee_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: >-
      Duration of the employee non-solicitation (anti-raiding) restriction,
      measured from the end of employment. Keep it finite and
      workforce-relationship-protective, not a substitute restraint on the
      employee's own work; North Dakota treats only a narrow anti-raiding
      formulation as outside the void restraint rule.
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: benchmark
    benchmark_ref: restrictive-covenant/employee-non-solicit-duration
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months matches the modal employee non-solicit term observed in
      benchmarked, publicly-filed employee agreements; 12 months is the common
      lighter alternative. North Dakota's law-backed limit is the narrow
      anti-raiding shape of the covenant, not a specific duration, so either
      finite term rides on keeping that shape.
  - name: covered_employee_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Look-back window before termination used to bound the class of Covered
      Employees to colleagues the employee actually worked with or supervised. A
      workforce-wide class adds nothing protective and pushes a lawful
      anti-raiding clause toward the kind of restraint North Dakota voids.
    display_label: Covered Employee Look-Back
    default: 12 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is a conservative look-back period that ties the covered class
      to recent working relationships instead of sweeping in the employer's
      entire workforce.
